Let $x$ be the number of ounces of pure water that must be added.  The total number of ounces of the resulting solution is $30+x$, and the number of ounces of acid in the resulting solution is $0.3\cdot30=9$ ounces.  The percentage of acid in the resulting solution is $\frac{9}{30+x}\cdot100\%$, which we set equal to $20\%$: \begin{align*}
\frac{9}{30+x}\cdot100\%&=20\%\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 9&=\frac{20}{100}(30+x)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 9&=\frac{6}{10}(30+x)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 90&=6(30+x)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 90&=180+6x\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 6x&=90-180=-90\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\boxed{15}
\end{align*}
