The sum of the first $n$ terms in the infinite geometric sequence $\left\{1,\frac{1}{3},\frac{1}{9},\frac{1}{27},\dots \right\}$ is $\frac{1-\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n}{1-\frac{1}{3}}=\frac{3}{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n\right)$.  We are given that this sum is $\frac{121}{81}$, so we can solve for $n$:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3}{2}\left(1-\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n\right)&=\frac{121}{81}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 1-\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n&=\frac{242}{243}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n&=1-\frac{242}{243}=\frac{1}{243}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^n&=\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^5\\
\Rightarrow\qquad n&=\boxed{5}
\end{align*}
Final Answer: The final answer is 5. I hope it is correct.

