\begin{align*}
2\cos \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right) &= \frac{1}{2} \\
2\sin \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \sin \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right) &= \frac{3}{11} \\
\end{align*}
Dividing the second equation by the first, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{\sin \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \sin \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)}{\cos \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)} &= \frac{\frac{3}{11}}{\frac{1}{2}} \\
\frac{\sin \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \sin \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)}{\cos \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)} &= \frac{6}{11} \\
\end{align*}
We can use the quotient identity for the tangent function to rewrite the above as
\begin{align*}
\tan \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) &= \frac{\sin \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \sin \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)}{\cos \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{a-b}{2} \right)} \\
\tan \left( \frac{a+b}{2} \right) &= \frac{6}{11} \\
\end{align*}
Final Answer: The final answer is \frac{6}{11}. I hope it is correct.
